[{"id":"VR188910","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows a galvanic cell consisting of two solutions in beakers, two metal electrodes, a voltmeter, and a salt bridge. The solution on the left is labeled 1.0 molar Z n with a positive 2 charge, aqueous. The solution on the right is labeled 1.0 molar A g with a positive 1 charge, aqueous. An electrode labeled Z n, solid, is partially submerged in the solution on the left. An electrode labeled A g, solid, is partially submerged in the solution on the right. A voltmeter is connected with wires to the two electrodes. Between each electrode and the voltmeter, each wire branches off and connect to a closed switch. A salt bridge connects the left and right beakers, with one end partially submerged in the solution in the left beaker, and the other end partially submerged in the solution in the right beaker.\" height=\"297\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR188910.g05.png\" width=\"300\" /></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Which of the following substances would be the best choice for filling the salt bridge in the galvanic cell shown above, and why?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VR188910_rubric","choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Distilled water, because it would avoid contaminating the solutions in the half-cells.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.0 molar H C l, aqueous\"><math alttext=\"1.0 molar H C l, aqueous\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>1.0</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mi>M</mi><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mtext>HCl</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>q</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because it would acidify the solutions and catalyze the overall cell reaction.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.0 molar C H 3 O H, aqueous\"><math alttext=\"1.0 molar C H 3 O H, aqueous\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>1.0</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mi>M</mi><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mtext>C</mtext><msub><mrow><mtext>H</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mtext>O</mtext><mtext>H</mtext><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>q</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because it would increase the <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"p H\"><math alttext=\"p H\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>p</mtext><mtext>H</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> of the solutions and catalyze the overall cell reaction.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\"><span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"1.0 molar K N O 3, aqueous\"><math alttext=\"1.0 molar K N O 3, aqueous\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>1.0</mn><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mi>M</mi><mspace depth=\"0.0ex\" height=\"0.0ex\" width=\"0.25em\"></mspace><mtext>K</mtext><mtext>N</mtext><msub><mrow><mtext>O</mtext></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msub><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>q</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, because the mobile ions would allow charge to flow between the half-cells.</p>"],"answer":3}]